    {
      "beat_id": "B01",
      "t_start": 0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 6,
      "narration_text": "Two electrons stay farther apart than chance predicts. No force pushes them. Nothing in the Hamiltonian changes. The wavefunction does it.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "headline": "Why Two Electrons Avoid Each Other With No Force",
        "kicker": "QUANTUM MECHANICS",
        "style": "title"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-exchange-stats/mp3/beat-B01.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.39,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-exchange-stats/clips/B01.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-exchange-stats/mp3/beat-B01.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "t_start": 6,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "For two distinguishable particles, the joint probability is simply |\u03c8\u2081(x\u2081)|\u00b2|\u03c8\u2082(x\u2082)|\u00b2. No preferred diagonal. No avoided region. Each particle is free to be anywhere.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-exchange-stats/mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 15.54,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-exchange-stats/clips/B02.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-exchange-stats/mp3/beat-B02.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "t_start": 16,
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Electrons are identical. If we can't say which is which, does the joint probability change? What forces the statistics?",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "headline": "What forces the statistics?",
        "style": "question"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-exchange-stats/mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 6.69,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-exchange-stats/clips/B03.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-exchange-stats/mp3/beat-B03.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "t_start": 25,
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "Identical fermions require an antisymmetric wavefunction: swap the two particles and the sign flips. Put them at the same x \u2014 \u03c8(x,x) = \u2212\u03c8(x,x) \u2014 which forces \u03c8 = 0 there.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-exchange-stats/mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 14.81,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-exchange-stats/clips/B04.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-exchange-stats/mp3/beat-B04.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "t_start": 36,
      "estimated_duration_s": 13,
      "narration_text": "That zero is a node that runs along the entire diagonal x\u2081 = x\u2082 of the joint-probability surface. The two electrons cannot sit at the same point \u2014 even without any repulsive force.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-exchange-stats/mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 13.61,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-exchange-stats/clips/B05.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-exchange-stats/mp3/beat-B05.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "t_start": 49,
      "estimated_duration_s": 4,
      "narration_text": "The mechanism: antisymmetry carves a permanent node.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "headline": "Antisymmetry carves a permanent node.",
        "style": "section"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-exchange-stats/mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 3.24,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-exchange-stats/clips/B06.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-exchange-stats/mp3/beat-B06.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "t_start": 53,
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "Bosons are symmetric \u2014 swap them, sign stays the same. Their diagonal becomes a ridge. Bosons bunch; fermions avoid. Opposite statistics from opposite signs.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-exchange-stats/mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.81,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-exchange-stats/clips/B07.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-exchange-stats/mp3/beat-B07.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "t_start": 65,
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "With no interaction term turned on, fermions average a larger separation than distinguishable particles; bosons average a smaller one. The exchange correlation is real \u2014 only the symmetry creates it.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-exchange-stats/mp3/beat-B08.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.98,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-exchange-stats/clips/B08.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-exchange-stats/mp3/beat-B08.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B09",
      "t_start": 77,
      "estimated_duration_s": 3,
      "narration_text": "No force. Just a sign.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "headline": "No force. Just a sign.",
        "style": "implication"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-exchange-stats/mp3/beat-B09.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 1.49,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-exchange-stats/clips/B09.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-exchange-stats/mp3/beat-B09.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B10",
      "t_start": 80,
      "estimated_duration_s": 13,
      "narration_text": "This is the engine behind the periodic table. Without antisymmetry, every electron would pile into the 1s orbital. Antisymmetry forces electrons into higher shells \u2014 atoms have size, matter has structure.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "STILL",
        "source": "ai",
        "motion": "hold",
        "remotion": {
          "pattern": "SlateCard",
          "provenance": "proven-core/SlateCard",
          "version": "1",
          "props": {
            "headline": "This is the engine behind the periodic table. Without antisymmetry, every\u2026",
            "eyebrow": "",
            "topic": "QUANTUM MECHANICS"
          },
          "rendered": {
            "out": "media/B10.mp4",
            "at": ""
          }
        }
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-exchange-stats/mp3/beat-B10.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 13.56,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-exchange-stats/clips/B10.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-exchange-stats/mp3/beat-B10.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B11",
      "t_start": 93,
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "The helium singlet-triplet energy difference \u2014 orthohelium vs parahelium \u2014 is the same effect. Different symmetry sectors, different probabilities of finding electrons close, different Coulomb energies. No extra force.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-exchange-stats/mp3/beat-B11.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 14.03,
